### Ecosystem packaging patterns

The biggest duplication pattern is not just rename drift. It is packaging drift:

- `SkyeSol/skyesol-main`
  - public brand/promo surfaces and site-integrated copies
- `Later-Additions/DonorCode-MySkyeApps/SuperIDEv3/.../public`
  - suite-packaged app copies
- `Later-Additions/DonorCode-MySkyeApps/SuperIDEv3/.../dist`
  - built/exported copies
- `AbovetheSkye-Platforms`
  - promoted standalone release candidates

That means one product may appear in four places:

- site-integrated surface
- suite source/public lane
- built dist lane
- standalone promoted lane

### Recommended canonicalization rules

If the goal is “one main standalone version with all upgrades and wired back in,” the cleanest rule set is:

- `SkyeDocx family`
  - canonical main: `AbovetheSkye-Platforms/SkyeDocxMax`
  - legacy aliases: `SkyeDocx`, `SkyeDocxPro`

- `WebPile family`
  - canonical main: donor `webpile-f500-v3.5.13` if verified stable
  - site-facing alias: `skyesol-main/WebPile Pro—Monaco Editor`

- `SovereignVariables`, `SkyeDrive`, `SkyeSheets`, `SkyeSlides`
  - canonical mains likely live in `SuperIDEv3.8/public/*`
  - SkyeSol copies should either become redirects or intentionally reduced public shells

- `kAIxU family`
  - canonical architecture should distinguish:
    - `kAIxU` brand/orchestrator
    - `Gateway13` runtime/control plane
    - themed app fronts
  - do not let every `kAIxU-*` front read like a separate core platform unless it has distinct implementation

- `SkyeFlow / SkyeRoutexFlow`
  - investigate feature parity and likely merge into one canonical flow/routing product line
